<div id="review_1009244271" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1009244271" />
    <a title="Addie H" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16858463-addie-h"><img alt="Addie H" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1511793475p2/16858463.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1009244271?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Addie H" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Addie H" href="/user/show/16858463-addie-h">Addie H</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6584520-lord-of-fire">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16858463-addie-h?shelf=4-word">4-word</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16858463-addie-h?shelf=zz-rereadfavs">zz-rereadfavs</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1009244271" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5821427770488884747">I am re-reading all my 5 star rated romance novels. There are 63 on my shelf (and counting). This is book 53. <br/><br/><i>(Tropes: Opposite Attract, Enemies to Lovers) </i> <br/><br/>This is how my 53rd re-read held up. <br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1613209159ra/30859365.gif' width='350' height='250' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>Holy crap…. This did not hold up. It’s been several years since I read it, but even knowing this book has a happy ending the entire book gave me a frightful chill. Being blackmailed and held against one’s will, no matter how hot your captor is - is not romantic or sigh worthy, no matter how much the prota</span>
  <span id="freeText5821427770488884747" style="display:none">I am re-reading all my 5 star rated romance novels. There are 63 on my shelf (and counting). This is book 53. <br><br><i>(Tropes: Opposite Attract, Enemies to Lovers) </i> <br><br>This is how my 53rd re-read held up. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1613209159ra/30859365.gif" width="350" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Holy crap…. This did not hold up. It’s been several years since I read it, but even knowing this book has a happy ending the entire book gave me a frightful chill. Being blackmailed and held against one’s will, no matter how hot your captor is - is not romantic or sigh worthy, no matter how much the protagonist redeems himself. A younger me clearly thought this was romantic. In 2021, this is just terrifying. The book was written almost 20 years ago, but even then did we really fall for this??<br><br>Changed from 5 stars to 1 star. <br><br>Short summary: Lucien blackmails/forces, Alice, the sister-in-law of his former lover to stay at his house. <br><br><i>- She appeared somewhere between the ages of eighteen and twenty-two—a wholesome, nay, a virginal beauty of trembling purity. He instantly knew that she was utterly untouched, impossible as that seemed in this place.<br><br>- “Miss Goody Two-Shoes,” he taunted softly.<br>She stiffened, sliding him a frown. “I do not appreciate being called that.”<br>His insolent gaze traveled over her body. “I hear you’re quite the little saint.”<br><br>- “Are you going to deny that we are extremely attracted to each other?”<br>His brazen question, so casually delivered, left her nigh speechless. “Do you really imagine you can succeed with me after you seduced my sister-in-law?”<br>“Do you really think you can resist?” he countered, his gray eyes flashing wickedly.</i><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1613209217ra/30859370.gif" width="250" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>- “You’re too young to realize it yet, but I know<br>what is going to happen to you.”<br>“You do?” she whispered, staring uneasily into his deep, crystalline eyes.<br>“I’ve seen it a thousand times. They’re going to make you just like everybody else, but I can protect you, your bright, beautiful soul. You’re in a cage and you don’t even know it, but I can free you. Let me take you under my wing. I can teach you how to outwit them if you’ll let me. I won’t let them turn you into another pretty, empty shell in ribbons and French silk. You are too good for that fate.”<br>His softly uttered words staggered her. It was as though he had looked into her soul and read her very heart. She stared at him, mesmerized. “What do you want of me?”<br>“The same thing you want, sweet,” he said as he stroked her hand in gentle reassurance. “Both of us, we just want someone to accept us for who we really are.”<br><br>- “One may go; the other shall stay for a while as my companion, provide me with a pleasant diversion—it grows so dull here in the country, don’t you know, but I leave it to you to decide, Alice . Who will go home to Harry and who will remain here at Revell Court . . . with me?”<br><br>- “Sit down, Miss Montague,” Lucien clipped out sternly. “You will not run away from this choice. You should be grateful I am willing to let one of you leave, for I am tempted to keep you both—but then, who would comfort poor little Harry?”<br><br>- She held her breath as he rapped softly on the door.<br>“Oh,Alice , my pet, come out and play,” he called urbanely.<br>She clutched the fire poker harder in her sweating hands. “Go away! I don’t want to see you!”<br>“Tut, tut, my dear, I know you are cross, but—”<br>“Cross?” she cried, taking an angry step toward the door, emboldened by the fact that he could not get to her, or if he did somehow, she would brain the cad. “Cross does not begin to describe my sentiments, Lucien Knight! What am I to think of you? One minute you are pointing a gun at me, the next you are reading me poetry!”<br>“But I thought you liked the poetry.”<br><br>- “Alice?”<br>She spun toward the door, her skirts whirling softly. “Yes?” she forced out.<br>“Do you know what I am holding in my hand?”<br>“No.”<br>“Care to guess?”<br>“A pitchfork?” she asked in a stilted attempt at levity, hoping to invoke his earlier, playful mood.<br>“No, my dear,” he answered drily. “A key to your room.”<br>“What?”she breathed, aghast.<br>“I should hate to have to use it.”<br>“You have a key to this room?”<br>“Mm-hmm.”</i><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1586623868ra/29275728.gif" width="250" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="5821427770488884747" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

