<div id="review_2213901327" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2213901327" />
    <a title="Ursula" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52878188-ursula"><img alt="Ursula" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1499351015p2/52878188.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2213901327?book_show_action=true">Dec 14, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ursula" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ursula" href="/user/show/52878188-ursula">Ursula</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=alpha-hero">alpha-hero</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=historical-romance">historical-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=hard-to-like-hero">hard-to-like-hero</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=independent-woman">independent-woman</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=adorable-heroine">adorable-heroine</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=angsty-goodness">angsty-goodness</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52878188-ursula?shelf=classic-rake">classic-rake</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2213901327" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1306096248947408550">An emotional 4.5 stars.<br/>I put off reading this one in the series because I did not like the sound of the hero, Lucien Knight, at all. And as I began reading the story- with some trepidation- I found my fears largely justified. He was a pretty horrible person. <br/>Whatever the excuses or explanations, he was a massive man-whore, one who thought nothing of indulging any selfish desire he had or, just as disappointingly, thought nothing of using sex as a means to an end. That end might have been vaguely</span>
  <span id="freeText1306096248947408550" style="display:none">An emotional 4.5 stars.<br />I put off reading this one in the series because I did not like the sound of the hero, Lucien Knight, at all. And as I began reading the story- with some trepidation- I found my fears largely justified. He was a pretty horrible person. <br />Whatever the excuses or explanations, he was a massive man-whore, one who thought nothing of indulging any selfish desire he had or, just as disappointingly, thought nothing of using sex as a means to an end. That end might have been vaguely linked to some patriotic duty <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ he was a spy for the Crown <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> but sex for him was just another form of currency used to buy or sell people or favours. His "orgies", ostensibly to find out information or recruit followers for the patriotic cause, were disgusting. <br />The <i>piece de resistance</i> was his blackmailing (effectively kidnapping) the heroine, Alice, to stay with him for a week directly after the orgy because he was in lust with her. He shamelessly used her love for her young nephew to do this. What a guy! So the first third of the book was a struggle for me to overcome my instinctive dislike of him.<br />What about Alice? I have read so many reviews that slam her big time. I just don't understand. I loved her. She was strong, principled, virtuous- yes, that old-fashioned word: virtuous- and these were exactly the qualities that attracted Lucien, a man who had fallen so low he no longer <b>had</b> any principles. <br />I feel one must acknowledge that it is Alice's strong personal code of honour, her <b> difference</b> from Lucien, that mean she can rescue him and help him rediscover the integrity and self-respect he thought he had lost. If you think she was mean and self-righteous and narrow-minded and should have been softer, more compassionate, (<i>more of a doormat!</i>) then I am saying that <b>that</b> kind of heroine would not have been able to snap Lucien out of his downward spiral. An easy victory for him would not have had him questioning his life-choices or contemplating any changes to them. He needed her to prove to him that deeply honourable, selfless people still existed in the world.<br />I was initially a bit sceptical of Lucien's rapid transit into vulnerability and sensitivity. The damage of years would not be healed so quickly. But I was swept up by the emotion and the passion, so that my disbelief faded and I just went along for the stormy ride.<br />In the end, I loved Lucien. Who would have thought it of little old (judgemental) me?? He needed to suffer and work really hard to win Alice - and ultimately, he deserved to win her. She did a couple of TSTL things at the end which I put down to immaturity, naiveté and, frankly, a justifiable scepticism where Lucien was concerned- he had a pretty shite track record, let's face it. (And just think of when they first meet!)<br />I must add, though, that the villainess was so OTT (as was the villain, in a way) that it bordered on the melodramatic. She was repulsive and it didn't make sense to me how Alice's brother could have been taken in by someone like her <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[(a very promiscuous, trailer-trash type) <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I am so happy I finally read this one. Lucien was ultimately a complex and damaged man who needed the purity and belief of a heroine like Alice to drag him out of the self-destructive pattern his life had assumed, and she needed the single-minded love and devotion that such a man could give her. A very satisfying read!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1306096248947408550" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

