<div id="review_2919251026" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2919251026" />
    <a title="Irene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36459924-irene"><img alt="Irene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627675581p2/36459924.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2919251026?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Irene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Irene" href="/user/show/36459924-irene">Irene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36459924-irene?shelf=regency-romances-and-bodice-rippers">regency-romances-and-bodice-rippers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2919251026" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1172645701632101904">The Draco pagan cult was a bit of a mess, and so was Lucien falling immediately in love with Alice, but Lord of Fire could have been worse. Lord of Fire is one of those dastardly stories that has enough good parts battling it out with the bad parts that, if you&apos;re like me, you can&apos;t come to a neat conclusion on whether or not it was worth reading. Are the bad parts excusable? But were the good parts <i> really </i> that good? While Lord of Fire certainly gives me more than enough doubts about its overa</span>
  <span id="freeText1172645701632101904" style="display:none">The Draco pagan cult was a bit of a mess, and so was Lucien falling immediately in love with Alice, but Lord of Fire could have been worse. Lord of Fire is one of those dastardly stories that has enough good parts battling it out with the bad parts that, if you're like me, you can't come to a neat conclusion on whether or not it was worth reading. Are the bad parts excusable? But were the good parts <i> really </i> that good? While Lord of Fire certainly gives me more than enough doubts about its overall quality, I also don't think it was a train wreck? <br /><br />Lord of Fire is what happens when you try to sanitize a story too much. It's as though romances published after the 1980s have an Outrageous Things Allowance before they have to dial it back down to a very safe place that is almost patronizing for how much they beat around the bush. I also wish Caro didn’t turn out to be such a predictable villain. I thought she was a flighty widow, but also hilarious when she told Lucien that if he got Alice pregnant he'd have to marry her. It was a disappointment that Caro remains a superficial character. "Pure” heroines like Alice are also not compelling. They're not exactly sticks in the mud, but they can't really do much up there on their pedestals, can they? And there's Lucien. He lost a lot of his bite after the first few chapters so there's just not much I have to say about him. <br /><br />I'm still under Foley's spell and at this point, I've pretty much committed to the series now. If you haven't read The Duke, the first book in the Knight Miscellany, start with that first.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1172645701632101904" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


