    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3746332323" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3746332323" />
    <a title="Morgan &amp; Many Books" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/65704259-morgan-many-books"><img alt="Morgan &amp; Many Books" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609082399p2/65704259.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3746332323?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Morgan &amp; Many Books" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Morgan &amp; Many Books" href="/user/show/65704259-morgan-many-books">Morgan &amp; Many Books</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3746332323" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12278286931248983707">I have very mixed feelings regarding... about 80% of this book, and so I tentatively give it <b>
  <i>3.5 stars</i>
</b>. <br/><br/>Lucien and Alice felt very underdeveloped for me, especially reading back to back with the preceding Book 1, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/958535.The_Duke__Knight_Miscellany___1_' title='The Duke (Knight Miscellany, #1) by Gaelen Foley' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Duke</a> in which the H/h were extremely nuanced characters (and is like, an astoundingly good piece of writing). Spy tropes are always a hit or a miss, and I think the miss part usually hinges on how much of the spy aspect hinges on some &apos;Enemy Spy&apos; who &apos;Did Something Terrible&apos; and</span>
  <span id="freeText12278286931248983707" style="display:none">I have very mixed feelings regarding... about 80% of this book, and so I tentatively give it <b>
  <i>3.5 stars</i>
</b>. <br /><br />Lucien and Alice felt very underdeveloped for me, especially reading back to back with the preceding Book 1, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/958535.The_Duke__Knight_Miscellany___1_" title="The Duke (Knight Miscellany, #1) by Gaelen Foley" rel="nofollow noopener">The Duke</a> in which the H/h were extremely nuanced characters (and is like, an astoundingly good piece of writing). Spy tropes are always a hit or a miss, and I think the miss part usually hinges on how much of the spy aspect hinges on some 'Enemy Spy' who 'Did Something Terrible' and therefore, 'It Can Only Be Me(the hero) To Kill The Enemy Spy'. <br /><br />Because of this aversion, I ended up skimming ever single page of spy-ness because... that is what the spy aspect of <b>Lord of Fire</b> was. Lucien hates Enemy Spy because #torture and Enemy Spy hates Lucien because--oh wait, what's that over there!? 800 other things to distract from the very feable reason given which is "Damn Lucien for not being broken by weeks of #torture"? <b>*Rolls Eyes*</b>. And the fact that I didn't lose any of the through-narrative as a result of skipping pages and pages of inner dialogue re: espionage...kind of speaks for itself? <br /><br />Compare the degree of research and detail in this to ,<b>The Duke</b>, and again, it falls very short. In fact, as I write this I am tempted to drop the rating further because I think <b>The Duke</b> really puts on display the integrity and potential that Gaelen Foley demonstrates as a writer: good, technical prose; well drawn characters; carefully developed romance; integrated secondary plots that serve the primary narrative. That in the second installement of <b>Knight Miscellany</b> (which, btw, is an EXCELLENT name for a series and tickles me pink that it is based on a historical aristocratic family) she totally did <i>not</i> hold up to the precedent she set for herself. <br /><br />So yeah, this is sort of the antithesis of all of that is good about <b>The Duke</b>? It's outlandish, it perpetuates the kidnapping trope that should have died twenty years prior to this book's publication, it delivers a hero &amp; heroine that are inconsistent and therefore difficult to invest in, it's bogged down with inner dialogue that seems directionless. <br /><br />The only reason I willingly give this a decent rating is because when Lucien and Alice have their 'moments' they were deeply moving, and the ending felt really great. Then again, I am sucker for a hero that is natural with children and when Lucien nuzzle's little Harry after <b>Scarface-ing</b> his Enemy Spy my ovaries exploded and my heart went to mush and evidently so did my mental faculties? <br /><br />Objectively, I can see the tropey deliciousness that has allowed <b>Lord of Fire</b> to outshine it's predecessor. That said, it was a bit of a mixed bag for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12278286931248983707" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


